## Sufficient Statistics

::: {#def-sufficient-statistic}

### Sufficient Statistic
A statistic $T=T(X)$ is sufficient for $\theta$ if one of the following conditions holds:

1.  **Log-Likelihood Difference:**
    For any pair of data sets $x$ and $y$ such that $T(x)=T(y)$, the difference in their log-likelihoods is constant with respect to $\theta$:
    $$
    \ell(\theta; x) - \ell(\theta; y) = c(x, y) \quad \text{for all } \theta
    $$
    where $c(x,y)$ depends only on $x$ and $y$, not on $\theta$.

2.  **Factorization Theorem:**
    $$
    f(x;\theta) = h(x) g(t(x);\theta)
    $$
    Where $h(x)$ is irrelevant to $\theta$.

3.  **Conditional Distribution:**
    The conditional distribution of $X$ given $T(X)=t$, denoted as $f(x|t(x), \theta)$, is independent of $\theta$.
    $$
    f(x|t(x), \theta) = f(x|t(x))
    $$

:::


```{r }
#| label: fig-par-log-likelihood
#| fig-cap: "Visualizing Parallel Log-Likelihoods"
#| echo: false
#| fig-align: "center"
#| message: false
#| warning: false
#| out.width: "70%"

library(ggplot2)

# Define range for theta
theta <- seq(0, 6, length.out = 300)

# Define log-likelihood functions

# Peak is set exactly at y = 4 to align with a grid line
ll_x <- -0.8 * (theta - 3)^2 + 4 

# The gap is set to 2, matching the grid spacing
const_diff <- 2
ll_y <- ll_x - const_diff

# Create data frame for plotting

# We use simple factor levels "A" and "B" for mapping, 

# then swap them for expressions in the scale functions
df <- data.frame(
  theta = rep(theta, 2),
  loglik = c(ll_x, ll_y),
  curve = rep(c("A", "B"), each = 300)
)

# Plot
ggplot(df, aes(x = theta, y = loglik, color = curve, linetype = curve)) +
  geom_line(linewidth = 1.2) +
  
  # Styling with Math Expressions in Legends
  scale_color_manual(
    values = c("blue", "red"),
    labels = expression(l(theta*"; "*x), l(theta*"; "*y))
  ) +
  scale_linetype_manual(
    values = c("solid", "dashed"),
    labels = expression(l(theta*"; "*x), l(theta*"; "*y))
  ) +
  
  # Force grid lines to align with the peaks and the gap
  scale_y_continuous(breaks = seq(-10, 10, by = 2)) +
  
  # Math expressions for axes
  labs(x = expression(theta), 
       y = expression(l(theta)),
       title = "Parallel Log-Likelihoods",
       subtitle = "Vertical difference is constant everywhere") +
  
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(legend.title = element_blank(),
        legend.position = "top",
        text = element_text(size = 12),
        plot.title = element_text(size = 12, face = "bold"),
        panel.grid.major.y = element_line(color = "gray60", linetype = "dotted"),
        panel.grid.minor.y = element_blank())

```


